&lt;p&gt;The pieris in are garden is flowering and is a magnet for all the bumble bees in Cornwall&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/dylan-snow/"&gt;Dylan&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/dylan-snow/4515890510/" title="Bee Pollen Looks Like Tiny Crack"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2772/4515890510_f736ba586c_m.jpg" width="240" height="170" alt="Bee Pollen Looks Like Tiny Crack" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Having allergy problems in Philly. My dad recommended pollen.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I ventured into the seedy underbelly of Philly's local sourcing scene (The Speakeasy) to procure some bee pollen.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
It looks like nature's crack rock. Bees kinda act like they are crack heads. Just watching the bees, they do the same thing.&lt;/p&gt;

