&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/dgmiami/"&gt;dgmiami&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/dgmiami/4722837313/" title="Bee in the Virginia Hills"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm2.static.flickr.com/1418/4722837313_da2d03af2b_m.jpg" width="240" height="232" alt="Bee in the Virginia Hills" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;ENJOY THE LARGEST VERSION!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
While waiting for the sunset over the Shenandoah Valley, this little guy was busy collecting before the evening was done.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
I swapped out to my 70-300mm lens, set the camera to servo focus, dropped my f-stop to 5.6 and started shooting before all the light - and the bee was gone for the night.  &lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Being extremely windy up on Skyline Drive, I was pleasantly surprised to have captured this shot.  Yes, I turned on the built-in Canon 7D flash for this one!&lt;/p&gt;

