&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/people/s0ulsurfing/"&gt;s0ulsurfing&lt;/a&gt; posted a photo:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/s0ulsurfing/4751623992/" title="Flight of the Bumblebee, Lensbaby remix"&gt;&lt;img src="http://farm5.static.flickr.com/4093/4751623992_4b574205ed_m.jpg" width="240" height="160" alt="Flight of the Bumblebee, Lensbaby remix" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Shooting these guys was a real challenge with the old manual focusing lensbaby 2.0, but the harder it was the more rewarding it felt to actually get the shot i had in my minds eye.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
If you like this sort of thing, there are 24 more images in the new &lt;a target="_blank" href="http://soulsurfing.photoshelter.com/gallery/2010-Lensbaby-Poppy-Pollination/G0000SOdn9emwdp0/" rel="nofollow"&gt;'2010 Lensbaby Poppy Pollination'&lt;/a&gt; gallery on my website.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;b&gt;*NOTE: added after question below.*&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;i&gt; I just checked the exposure of this and the last shot in lightroom, it says 1/250 here and 1/400 on the last, but the wings are more blurred on the last one! Both taken with the lensbaby (not 50mm as both flickr and lightroom read) and the f5.6 aperture ring. So i can only guess it has a lot to do with....&lt;br /&gt;
1. The strength and angle of light&lt;br /&gt;
2. The speed at which the wings were beating at the time. &lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
